│ "thoughts": "1. Understanding the Issue:\nEarlyCSE crashes when attempting to │
│ CSE two calls to the commutative intrinsic llvm.smin.i32 that differ in their │
│ call site attribute sets (one has the strictfp attribute, the other does      │
│ not). The crash occurs in combineIRFlags(), specifically at the assertion     │
│ that attribute intersection must succeed for callsites that were considered   │
│ identical earlier in the pass.\n\n2. Analyzing opt's Log:\nThe debug log      │
│ shows: EarlyCSE CSE:   %call2 ... to: %call ... #1 meaning EarlyCSE decided   │
│ the second intrinsic call (%call2) is redundant and should be replaced by the │
│ first (%call). This decision precedes combineIRFlags(), which tries to merge  │
│ IR flags and callsite attributes. The assertion failure indicates the earlier │
│ equivalence test allowed matching of these two calls even though their        │
│ attributes cannot be intersected.\n\n3. Root Cause Analysis:\nLooking at      │
│ EarlyCSE.cpp, equality for value numbering relies on                          │
│ DenseMapInfo<SimpleValue>::isEqualImpl(). For non-identical instructions,     │
│ special cases allow commuted equality: lines 396–404 contain logic for        │
│ commutative intrinsics:\n\nif (LII && RII && LII->getIntrinsicID() ==         │
│ RII->getIntrinsicID() && LII->isCommutative() && LII->arg_size() >= 2) {\n    │
│ return LII->getArgOperand(0) == RII->getArgOperand(1) && ... }\n\nThis branch │
│ ignores callsite attributes entirely. Thus two commutative intrinsic calls    │
│ with mismatched attributes are treated as equal. Later, combineIRFlags()      │
│ assumes (via the assert) that any calls deemed identical have attribute sets  │
│ that can be intersected; it invokes tryIntersectAttributes(To <- From). For   │
│ our reproducer the first path (normal identical check) fails due to differing │
│ attributes; then the commutative intrinsic path returns true based only on    │
│ operands, so equality succeeds. However attribute intersection later fails,   │
│ triggering the assertion. Therefore the invariant “calls judged equal must    │
│ have intersectable attributes” is broken specifically for the commutative     │
│ intrinsic fallback.\n\n4. Proposed Edit Point(s):\nModify the commutative     │
│ intrinsic equality branch in isEqualImpl (lines 396–404) to also verify that  │
│ the attribute sets can be intersected (same test used in hasSameSpecialState  │
│ / Instruction::hasSameSpecialState for calls when IntersectAttrs=true). If    │
│ the intersection fails, return false instead of treating the instructions as  │
│ equal. This restores the invariant assumed by combineIRFlags(). Concretely,   │
│ insert an attribute intersection check before returning true in the           │
│ commutative intrinsic block:\n\nPseudo-diff:\n--- before\nif (LII && RII &&   │
│ ... ) {\n  return operands_commute_match && other_args_match;\n}\n---         │
│ after\nif (LII && RII && ... ) {\n  if                                        │
│ (!LII->getAttributes().intersectWith(LII->getContext(),                       │
│ RII->getAttributes()).has_value())\n    return false;\n  return               │
│ operands_commute_match && other_args_match;\n}\n\nThis change ensures calls   │
│ with non-intersectable attribute sets (like differing strictfp presence if    │
│ that cannot be intersected) are not CSE'd, avoiding the assertion in          │
│ combineIRFlags.\n\n5. Conclusion:\nThe crash is due to attribute-insensitive  │
│ equality for commutative intrinsics in EarlyCSE, violating an internal        │
│ invariant relied upon later. Adding an attribute intersection feasibility     │
│ check to the commutative intrinsic equality path prevents misclassification   │
│ and resolves the abort without weakening correctness. After this fix EarlyCSE │
│ will refuse to CSE such mismatched calls, and combineIRFlags will no longer   │
│ encounter impossible attribute intersections.\n"})                            │
