│                                                                               │
│ ### Root Cause Analysis ###                                                   │
│                                                                               │
│ -------------------- BEGIN --------------------                               │
│ 1. Understanding the Issue:                                                   │
│ EarlyCSE crashes when attempting to CSE two calls to the commutative          │
│ intrinsic llvm.smin.i32 that differ in their call site attribute sets (one    │
│ has the strictfp attribute, the other does not). The crash occurs in          │
│ combineIRFlags(), specifically at the assertion that attribute intersection   │
│ must succeed for callsites that were considered identical earlier in the      │
│ pass.                                                                         │
│                                                                               │
│ 2. Analyzing opt's Log:                                                       │
│ The debug log shows: EarlyCSE CSE:   %call2 ... to: %call ... #1 meaning      │
│ EarlyCSE decided the second intrinsic call (%call2) is redundant and should   │
│ be replaced by the first (%call). This decision precedes combineIRFlags(),    │
│ which tries to merge IR flags and callsite attributes. The assertion failure  │
│ indicates the earlier equivalence test allowed matching of these two calls    │
│ even though their attributes cannot be intersected.                           │
│                                                                               │
│ 3. Root Cause Analysis:                                                       │
│ Looking at EarlyCSE.cpp, equality for value numbering relies on               │
│ DenseMapInfo<SimpleValue>::isEqualImpl(). For non-identical instructions,     │
│ special cases allow commuted equality: lines 396–404 contain logic for        │
│ commutative intrinsics:                                                       │
│                                                                               │
│ if (LII && RII && LII->getIntrinsicID() == RII->getIntrinsicID() &&           │
│ LII->isCommutative() && LII->arg_size() >= 2) {                               │
│   return LII->getArgOperand(0) == RII->getArgOperand(1) && ... }              │
│                                                                               │
│ This branch ignores callsite attributes entirely. Thus two commutative        │
│ intrinsic calls with mismatched attributes are treated as equal. Later,       │
│ combineIRFlags() assumes (via the assert) that any calls deemed identical     │
│ have attribute sets that can be intersected; it invokes                       │
│ tryIntersectAttributes(To <- From). For our reproducer the first path (normal │
│ identical check) fails due to differing attributes; then the commutative      │
│ intrinsic path returns true based only on operands, so equality succeeds.     │
│ However attribute intersection later fails, triggering the assertion.         │
│ Therefore the invariant “calls judged equal must have intersectable           │
│ attributes” is broken specifically for the commutative intrinsic fallback.    │
│                                                                               │
│ 4. Proposed Edit Point(s):                                                    │
│ Modify the commutative intrinsic equality branch in isEqualImpl (lines        │
│ 396–404) to also verify that the attribute sets can be intersected (same test │
│ used in hasSameSpecialState / Instruction::hasSameSpecialState for calls when │
│ IntersectAttrs=true). If the intersection fails, return false instead of      │
│ treating the instructions as equal. This restores the invariant assumed by    │
│ combineIRFlags(). Concretely, insert an attribute intersection check before   │
│ returning true in the commutative intrinsic block:                            │
│                                                                               │
│ Pseudo-diff:                                                                  │
│ --- before                                                                    │
│ if (LII && RII && ... ) {                                                     │
│   return operands_commute_match && other_args_match;                          │
│ }                                                                             │
│ --- after                                                                     │
│ if (LII && RII && ... ) {                                                     │
│   if (!LII->getAttributes().intersectWith(LII->getContext(),                  │
│ RII->getAttributes()).has_value())                                            │
│     return false;                                                             │
│   return operands_commute_match && other_args_match;                          │
│ }                                                                             │
│                                                                               │
│ This change ensures calls with non-intersectable attribute sets (like         │
│ differing strictfp presence if that cannot be intersected) are not CSE'd,     │
│ avoiding the assertion in combineIRFlags.                                     │
│                                                                               │
│ 5. Conclusion:                                                                │
│ The crash is due to attribute-insensitive equality for commutative intrinsics │
│ in EarlyCSE, violating an internal invariant relied upon later. Adding an     │
│ attribute intersection feasibility check to the commutative intrinsic         │
│ equality path prevents misclassification and resolves the abort without       │
│ weakening correctness. After this fix EarlyCSE will refuse to CSE such        │
│ mismatched calls, and combineIRFlags will no longer encounter impossible      │
│ attribute intersections.                                                      │
│                                                                               │
│ --------------------  END  --------------------                               │
│                                                                               │
